<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1887-10-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1887-10-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="484" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                        <head>No. 29.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Sir <persName type="from">L. S.
                                    Sackville West</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Bayard</persName></hi>.</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1887-10-19"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 19,
                                1887</date>. (Received October 21.)</dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to inform you that I am
                            instructed by the Marquis of Salisbury, Her Majesty’s principal
                            secretary of state for foreign affairs, to protest against the seizure
                            of the Canadian vessel <hi rend="italic">Alfred Adams</hi>, in Behring
                            Seas, and against the continuation of similar proceedings by the United
                            States authorities on the high seas.</p>
                        <p>I have, etc.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">L. S. Sackville
                            West.</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>